CDU convention in January. Delay due to covid. https://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2020/12/16/commentary/world-commentary/angela-merkel-germanys-next-leader/

It has now been confirmed that the party convention, which is the electing body, will take place online only in mid-January 2021. The election will then be confirmed by an additional mail-in election afterwards, so that the final result should be confirmed by end of 22 January 2021. The winner of the digital election will then be the only candidate on the mail-in ballot, as all candidates confirmed they will withdraw from the mail-in election in case the do not win the first round.

AKK said there is no doubt the party meeting will not happen in 2020 yesterday, now *all* candidates conform, even Merz. Paul Zimiak, secretary general of the CDU, now confirms that all candidates agreed to probably hold the party meeting in mid-January, preferring an in-person meeting to all other options. However, a fully distanced, digital only meeting and voting becomes more likely, since either the German party law will be amended in that direction with the subsequent support of social democrat SPD now, or the existing law proves to be pandemic-proof with respect to judicial clarity with regards to online-only voting, as it is currently checked on behalf of the president of the German parliament, Wolfgang Schäuble.

Personal post-mortem and an explanation for anyone, who would like to understand the decision to postpone the congress (no date mentioned, it purely depends on the development with Covid-19 and could theoretically even happen in 2020, if things got better): there are at least two theories about it, and both are plausible: 1) Merz claims, it was "huge parts of the party leadership, who wanted to prevent him from becoming party leader". True to a certain degree. Merkel and others wanted Laschet or Spahn, not him. Various reasons for that. 2) They knew, that a second (partial) lockdown was inevitable (it will start on monday), and you can´t stay credible when telling the population to have no contacts and yourself having meetings - no matter how small and secure they might be.
The lockdown could prolong what is becoming a political stalemate. Impasse. Patt (in German).

Germany is not quite Japan, but "slowly building a majority among voting delegates" is code for "there is nobody else". There was a short window of opportunity this summer for the candidates to showcase their credentials, and Merz and Rottgen missed it. That window has now closed with 6000 daily Covid cases. I also think that there is still the odd chance of postponement in case of a public health emergency. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-germany-politics-laschet-idUSKBN26Q0MK

Concerning Spahn: do voters like incredibility and opportunistic shifts? I don´t think so at all (and Spahn is clever enough to see that too of course). German left-wing media would totally focus on that, if Laschet drew back. Now they´re promoting Spahn, and if he got candidate, they would try to destroy him afterwards as "illoyal", "opportunistic" etc.. German media games only. If they quote minor opinions from less important CDU people, it´s for their own ideological reasons only.
It would surprise me if Spahn actually ran, but new articles make this a possibility. I think other people are over-updating.

There are reports that several CDU MPs of the German parliament ("Bundestagsabgeordnete"), among them some high-ranking with function in the party leadership ("CDU-Präsidium") are not contempt with the applicants to chose from, and thus encourage Jens Spahn (federal minister of public health, currently supporting the application of Armin Laschet) to apply for leadership himself. It appears the race is much more open still than I assumed; maybe they're right in the middle of a party wing fight, and its time for kicks and knuckles.

Latest news from inside CDU: AKK and the three candidates had a meeting yesterday to discuss the "candidate process". They agreed to very specific dates for each of them (nobody mentioned anyone but those three, so no "someone else" in the game anymore; the media are still speculating about Spahn, but in AKK´s mail to the members there is no room for that option) when to speak online to the public (calendar weeks 46 and 48) and to the members only (calendar week 47). So it´s basically down to Laschet vs. Merz. According to german magazine "Spiegel" CDU members still favor Merz (see article below), but a) it´s party delegates who wil vote, and they have their own agenda b) the journalists at Spiegel hate Merz, but hope for him to became party leader to make it easier for their left-wing / green friends to get more votes next year. They will write, whatever it takes, to work on that - and then shoot him down big style afterwards.

Latest idea / rumors (from German magazine Focus) for a compromise: Laschet (if elected against Merz or Merz voluntarily gives it up) to become CDU party leader, the other candidates are promised nice posts in the next cabinet, too. Depending on opinion polls in December Söder or Spahn to become chancellor candidate, if Laschet´s popularity in the population doesn´t increase till then. That would not be a very attractive perspective for Laschet, but he is said to be determined to go for it anyway. Söder might indeed prefer staying in Bavaria (he´s been saying so for months now). With Laschet and Merz both being VERY clear about wanting to be party leader, I´m now quite sure, that Spahn will not be it.

1) They seem to plan to hold it to elect a new party leader "whatever happens", so down a little for bin 5: https://www.rtl.de/cms/cdu-parteitag-im-dezember-mit-bling-bling-gegen-corona-4613113.html Very strict restrictions planned: measuring fever at the entrance, everybody has her/his specific place, etc. (the typical stuff). Interesting new one: everyone needs to wear technical devices that beeps, if two people come closer to each other than two metres. And they´re flexible about the exact locations (even football stadiums are being discussed). Looks realistic, that it can be done like that, even if the Covid-19 situation should get worse. 2) No sign for Spahn to change his mind to back up Laschet, so down again a little for bin 4. 3) No apparent reason, why Röttgen´s chances should have changed. 4) Laschet and Merz with equally high probability: Laschet has most of the party leadership behind him and has just won local elections with in NRW, Merz has the sympathy of more of the party members. As the speeches of the candidates will play a big role, for whom the delegates vote, Merz could have a slight disadvantage: under Covid-19 conditions he might be less able to use his rhetoric brilliance to influence them.
Update: I have slightly increased Laschets chance of winning after the CDU showed good results in local elections in Northrine Westphalia, which will give critics less room for attacks

Soder (CSU) is seen as the most popular politician in Germany but being attacked by the left wing press (which may be a good thing). Merz is more likely than Lanchet to offer himself as number two in a ticket with Soder. Lanchet has lost popularity with the voters due his performance during the Covid-19 lockdown. The Novichok/Navalny has raised the profile of Rottgen with conservatives by hardening Germany’s approach to Russia and could provide a good number two to Soder’s softer approach as a potential ticket. It would appear that the CDU is looking to elect the best running mate for Soder as opposed to a Leader/Chancellor.

To understand this question correctly, I am assuming that it is the Leader of the CDU rather than the CDU/CSU (and therefore the replacement of Angela Merkel to be the next chancellor) that is being looked for. If it is the CDU alone then I would propose Friedrich Merz as he would be the favourite to beat Habeck of the opposition Green Party. However, if it is the leader of the CDU/CSU then I would propose Markus Soder to be the frontrunner. Can Soder become the leader of a C DU/CSU alliance as they are considered sister parties who do not compete federally? A clarification of this could alter my probabilities.

Although I don't think it's impossible for practical reasons that the CDU will decide to leave everything as it was for the next two years, which would mean A K-K remains party leader and the answer may be "A new leader will not be elected" on these grounds, two things are important to keep in mind, which point to A K-K in person, and in her current function.
I would not have expect that clarification result I asked for (see above: note 25 August), but now we´ve got it. Makes this even more complicated.
Following @pstamp lead on this one. Does Angela have a sister?
In addition to @pstamp's analysis, Laschet's path to victory is the same as Röttgen's: lead the not-Merz camp. So Röttgen goes to epsilon.

Tobias Hans (CDU, Saarland MP) stated recently that planning for the December Parteitag is on schedule and that it will be executed however possible. He also stated once more, how important that congress will be for the party and its compliance with German party law, and that all options, including virtualization, are considered and precautions are being taken to make it happen. Negotiations for necessary changes in German party law (that currently prevent virtual congresses from being recognized as such) have started, so I exclude the option of another postponement or cancellation from now on. Armin Laschet (CDU, Northrhine-Westphalia MP) was recently visited by Angela Merkel in his state, which was reminiscent of Merkel's visit to Markus Söder and his state government in mid-July. He showed her the remains of the industrial heritage of the Ruhrgebiet (e.g. Zeche Zollverein in the city of Essen) instead of baroque gilden castles, which may point to his intention to be more eligible to work class and middle class-people. First and foremost, it appears to show Merkel's support and approval for Laschet, however not exclusively for Laschet. I still favor Röttgen for his deep knowledge and understanding of foreign policy, which seems crucial in this age of virulent, interwoven and complex conflicts, he'd also stand for continuity in one of Merkel's leitmotifs, "Ausgleich" (balance). However, there's a fine line to inactivity and hesitation he'd have to overcome. I still can't imagine Friedrich Merz's successful comeback into politics - no way. I can't imagine Merkel showing her approval of his ahead of the Parteitag either, so there will be no visit to Friedrich Merz whatsoever - where should Merkel travel, to his private yacht in the Mediterranean? Where would they meet, in "Haus Sauvigny" in Brilon, where his old money family has been seated? https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haus_Sauvigny In times like these, having no responsibility and thus no opportunity to prove one's capacity is a big handicap. The only way out for Merz is his close ties to all sorts of industrial lobby groups, which start to play and polarize between unions and employers, whine for subsidies, warn of bankruptcies, layoffs and a futures lack of vocational education spots or simply demand more taxpayers' money or outright tax cuts. They've done so at all times, in good and bad times, in boom and bust, so it wouldn't mean a thing - except more pressure on "green" regulation and other rational policies, all of which Friedrich Merz would happily deliver.

Things don't go well for Markus Söder (CSU) and his aspiration becoming the next chancellor of Germany in the 2021 general election. Things started well, when Bavaria announced it will arrange mobile testing stations for SARS-CoV-2 next to German main transit roads towards the Southeast of European neighbor countries (Austria, Czech Republic mainly), so people can get tested safely and quickly when returning home from travel not only on the airports (MUC introduced airport testing sites very early), but also for people who enter Germany making their trip by car. On 12 August 2020 it went public that 44,000 of the tests taken among car passengers, which resulted in 900 positive cases among residents across Germany, have not yet lead to any action according to guidelines (notification, quarantine, reporting,...) after days and weeks. About 100 further positive test results could not be assigned to the respective citizen or person tested. They obviously got missed out by public health administration somehow.
Maintaining current forecast.

A little more for Merz. I so far had not included the public opinion in the eastern states enough. They (and their delegates) like Merz very much. Instead of voting AfD they might come back to CDU with Merz as the new party leader. Some of them are still in "GDR-mode" (voting for post-communist Die Linke (still the same party as former PDS, and SED (GDR communist rulers) before that)), but many others don´t want anything less than more left-wing politics. Merz would be a way out for them.

There are tons of uncertainty in here, so just a very short summary... 1) The regular party congress will happen in December (no megahuge second wave in Germany to be expected), and they will elect a party leader (AKK would not just "stay in office" (even if she would like to continue (=another "someone else"), there would be an election). No serious doubt about that . Bin 5: 0% 2) Merz: lost against AKK last time; the opinion polls concerning being chancellor candidate are against him (Laschet/Spahn together oder Söder are too tough competition); he would only really want to, if he could get chancellor. Bin 2: 20% 3) Röttgen: could be the one to let Söder be chancellor candidate for CDU+CSU together (which Laschet and Merz would not accept for themselves). Bin 3: 20% 4) Laschet: would only go for it together with (a) Spahn as his wingman AND (b) with a chance to be chancelor candidate, where Söder is huge competition (Laschet has too much to loose otherwise). Bin 1: 20% 5) Spahn could go for it himself (he would accept being "only" party leader for a while without a chance for becoming chancelor); same with AKK. Bin 4: 30% for Spahn plus 10 for AKK
Perhaps treading water will work.

Merkel is on a visit to Bavaria right now and was invited, for the first time in the past 15 years, to take part in a session of the Bavarian state government. The pictures, or photo-ops, that are a likely reason for this vist

It is also much more likely that a candidate who is not part of the "same-old" Berlin-centric mainstream will be chosen - quite probably Söder from Bayern.

@SE_Meyer has a very good summary of the recent history of the CDU leadership race, that I largely agree with. However there are two questions following from his/her list of weaknesses of the candidates (and I agree at least Merz and Laschet would lead to significant losses for the CDU, if not immediately then through their sheer incompetence): - Who will be elected by the party officials (which most likely don't agree with our analysis)? - If none of the current candidates are deemed competent enough: Who else will seek and take the leadership role?
This is a decision about the future path of the CDU. A move to the right, or more of the status quo.
